    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-01-14T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-01-14T09:00:00-05:00" n="231"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d231">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.5/1–1451: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_GWS1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gifford</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-01-14T14:00:00+00:00"
                            >January 14, 1951—2 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3901. From <persName corresp="#p_MDI1">MacArthur</persName> for <persName
                        corresp="#p_PGW1">Perkins</persName>. Remytel 1001, January 11 from The
                    Hague, repeated Madrid 4.<note n="1" xml:id="d231fn1">Not printed. In it
                            <persName corresp="#p_MDI1">MacArthur</persName> reported that he had
                        heard that <persName corresp="#p_SJK1">Joseph Kingsbury Smith</persName>, a
                        correspondent for International News Service, who was in Europe reporting on
                        the <persName corresp="#p_E1">Eisenhower</persName> tour, had sent a message
                        to General <persName corresp="#p_FYBF1">Franco</persName> asking him if he
                        would invite <persName corresp="#p_E1">Eisenhower</persName> to visit
                        Madrid. (740.5/1–1151)</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SJK1">Joe Kingsbury Smith</persName> asked to see me
                    privately and unofficially this morning. He referred to the message which he had
                    sent to <persName corresp="#p_FYBF1">Franco</persName> and said that on January
                    11 <persName corresp="#p_LMMDLI1">Lojendio</persName> (counselor of Spanish
                    Embassy Paris) called on him in The Hague. <persName corresp="#p_LMMDLI1"
                        >Lojendio</persName> asked whether General <persName corresp="#p_E1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName> or US Government had knowledge of and approved
                        <persName corresp="#p_SJK1">Smith</persName>’s message to <persName
                        corresp="#p_FYBF1">Franco</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_SJK1"
                        >Smith</persName> said he replied that the initiative came solely from
                        <gloss target="#t_INS1">INS</gloss>.</p>
                <pb facs="0463" n="425" xml:id="pg_425"/>
                <p>Lojendio allegedly told him that while <persName corresp="#p_FYBF1"
                        >Franco</persName> would be glad to see <persName corresp="#p_E1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName> and would even be willing to travel to the
                    Spanish-Portuguese frontier or Lisbon to meet with him, <persName
                        corresp="#p_FYBF1">Franco</persName> would only give <persName
                        corresp="#p_SJK1">Smith</persName> a reply for publication after he was
                    certain that <persName corresp="#p_E1">Eisenhower</persName> would agree to such
                    a meeting. <persName corresp="#p_SJK1">Smith</persName> said he told <persName
                        corresp="#p_LMMDLI1">Lojendio</persName> that in his own (<persName
                        corresp="#p_SJK1">Smith</persName>’s) judgment there was no possibility of
                        <persName corresp="#p_E1">Eisenhower</persName> seeing <persName
                        corresp="#p_FYBF1">Franco</persName> on his trip to the <gloss
                        target="#t_NATO1">NAT</gloss> capitals and <persName corresp="#p_LMMDLI1"
                        >Lojendio</persName> allegedly replied that in this event matter should be
                        dropped.<note n="2" xml:id="d231fn2">In telegram 3923, January 16, from
                        London, <persName corresp="#p_MDI1">MacArthur</persName> reported that
                            <persName corresp="#p_SJK1">Smith</persName> had phoned him that
                        afternoon stating that he, <persName corresp="#p_SJK1">Smith</persName>, had
                        received a telephone invitation from <persName corresp="#p_LMMDLI1"
                            >Lojendio</persName> to proceed to Madrid for an interview with
                            <persName corresp="#p_FYBF1">Franco</persName>. <persName
                            corresp="#p_SJK1">Smith</persName> was disinclined to accept the
                        invitation, but he asked <persName corresp="#p_MDI1">MacArthur</persName> to
                        authorize him, in a confidential message to <gloss target="#t_INS1"
                            >INS</gloss> headquarters in New York, to state that General <persName
                            corresp="#p_E1">Eisenhower</persName> preferred that <persName
                            corresp="#p_SJK1">Smith</persName> not hold the interview. <persName
                            corresp="#p_MDI1">MacArthur</persName> replied that he had no such
                        authority, that his conversations with <persName corresp="#p_SJK1"
                            >Smith</persName> had been strictly personal, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_SJK1">Smith</persName> would have to be guided by his own
                        conscience in the matter. (740.5/1–1651)</note>
                </p>
                <p>I told <persName corresp="#p_SJK1">Smith</persName> that in my personal opinion
                    his initiative in this matter seemed designed to create publicity and confusion
                    and did not serve the best interests of the US, the other <gloss
                        target="#t_NATO1">NAT</gloss> countries, General <persName corresp="#p_E1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName> and for that matter <persName corresp="#p_FYBF1"
                        >Franco</persName> himself. I also told him that he should not consider his
                    private meeting with me as constituting any form of channel to General <persName
                        corresp="#p_E1">Eisenhower</persName>. He said he understood this and added
                    that I was free to deny we had even talked about this matter. [<persName
                        corresp="#p_MDI1">MacArthur</persName>.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GWS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gifford</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
